segments.text: and they need some help.
And I said, well, what do you want me to do?
He said, I would like for you to tutor them in English, accounting, and algebra.
And I said, I don't know if I can do that because, you know, we've got to
I just got married and we've got a heavy spring load coming up here in track.
And he said, we will pay you $1 per student per hour.
I said, dog, you've got a deal.
So I had four or five students in each subject.
And I went downtown in Bryan and
rented an old Victor Comptometer that had the arm on it you would pull to use as an addition, subtraction, and multiplying function for accounting.
And I would teach those guys the double entry method of accounting that Homer Adams, class of 45, taught us.
So you're a freshman helping freshmen.
That's right.
And Dog figured it'd be better that way, you know,
I was one of them.
They were one of us.
And they were having to repeat first semester accounting, algebra, and English.
So by the end of the course, they all passed.
I think the lowest grade any of them made was a C. Yeah, pretty good.
So it worked.
Where did you do this physically?
In H-Ramp.

of Hart Hall there was a lounge on the first floor and couches and chairs and a table or two and a coke machine and we'd get over in the corner at this chair and we'd sit there and I would drum into them about rhetoric composition and punctuation and cut off your dangling participles and use a semicolon instead of a colon and
You know, use an apostrophe where it belongs.
Make sure you don't put the word only in the wrong position as a modifier.

Those kinds of things that we all learned in high school, but some of the guys didn't have the advantage from the smaller schools, didn't have the advantage of good instruction, or they just disregarded punctuation and spelling altogether.
Did you do that later semesters or just that one time?
Just that one time, well, I take that back.
In my sophomore year, dog came to me again and asked me to tutor a couple of guys in accounting, which I was very happy to do under the same arrangement.
I sure could use the money.
Let's see, we mentioned also a while ago,
Now, you didn't have to worry about having a date because you had a wife pretty quickly.
Oh, yeah.
But how did the other guys get dates, and how did they make links with the Tessie girls and so forth?
Well, some of the guys got dates from downtown Bryan, but they were sort of few and far between because, after all, you've got 5,000 bachelors and 1,000 married guys out here on the campus.
Those 5,000 bachelors, if they're hometown sweethearts, you're not coming up here to see them on the weekend.
They're going to go down to Bryan and see what's available down there.
And that ratio gets pretty thin and out of kilter.
The Tessies would come down.
And a lot of the Aggies had girlfriends at TSCW.
And they would come down on the train.
But one of the things that you could count on at every home football game

and particularly at Sabisa Hall, I couldn't speak for Duncan Hall over on the other side of the campus, but at Sabisa Hall where all the athletes ate, about noon on football Saturdays, two or three buses would pull up from TSCW, the driver would open those doors, and those girls would come fogging off of that bus, screaming and giggling and laughing at the top of their lungs,
and they would see these freshmen and sophomores and juniors walking around, leaving Savisa on their way back to their dorms to get ready for the march in.
And you talk about a jailbreak.
The guys would look over their shoulders and see these girls getting off the bus, and to be charitable, I'm sure they were nice girls.
But I wouldn't have cared to date any of them.
But they sure could run fast.
And they would capture dates, literally capture them.
And the guys would take them to the ball game, and they'd have dates that night, and we'd have a dance later on.
And a good time was had by all, I suppose.
Some of the big-time groups that came here to perform, who were some of those people?
Big orchestras.
We had Racing with the Moon, Vaughn Monroe.
We had Les Brown and his band of renown with Bob Hope and his group of young Hollywood starlets.
They performed in Kyle Field.
Oh, gee.
The Dorseys?
No, we didn't have any of the Dorseys while we were here.
It just escapes me right now.
But we did have some big name bands.
Let's see.
OK, now that's all the notes that I made.
Do you have any other topics you can think of that we should have?
No.
I told you about Bones turning off the lights in Kyle Field.
Oh, an aside about Bones.
Bones was the class of 25 here at Texas A&M.
He was also a well-renowned tackle in the Southwest Conference.
My father went to a small agricultural
It wasn't a college.
It was a school in Russellville, Arkansas.
It was called Arkansas Polytechnic Institute.
What it was really was just a continuation of a more advanced senior high school when he first joined there from Hendricks College in Conway.
He went to Hendricks his first year and then transferred to Arkansas Tech when his folks moved from Danville, Arkansas and Yale County to Polk County, Russellville.
My dad was an all-state halfback and the state 102-20 champion and also all-Arkansas intercollegiate in baseball.
as was the habit of small schools in those days, they would get a Pullman car and they would travel around the United States playing bigger teams, offering themselves up to the slaughter.
But Arkansas Tech was a little different.
They had some guys that had been playing football there four, five, and six years.
which was illegal in those days because there were no rules that applied to them.
And they put together a hell of an aggregation of athletes.
And they went around playing bigger schools until these schools finally wouldn't play them because they were afraid of losing on their home ground.
Anyhow, they came on a swing down through Texas.
They played Austin College.
They played Russ College.
They played Trinity College.
And they played Texas A&M here at Kyle Field.
My dad talked about the trip, especially here at Kyle Field.
It was in September.
It was hot still and of course the train had no air conditioning in those days and they would sleep with the Pullman windows open.
Mosquitoes were terrible.
The coach would
stay up all night burning rags to keep the mosquitoes away so the boys could sleep.
And my dad said that they had heard tales, fables, about the terrific linemen and hard-hitting backs that Texas A&M had.
One lineman in particular was Bones Irvins.
He got his name Bones because he broke so many bones when he tackled.
And another was Taro Kishi from Orange, Texas.
And Taro was a bone-crunching halfback, although it turned out that Taro weighed about 150 pounds, which is about what my dad weighed.
Anyhow, they lined up and played against Texas A&M out here.
They lost 42 to nothing, but they gave a pretty good account of themselves.
And he said he got hit by a bone and said that was the hardest he'd ever been tackled in his life.
And that year, later on that same year, this was 1924, Arkansas Tech became the first school west of the Mississippi to play West Point.
They took a train, special train, from the state of Arkansas up there and then played and lost.
He said that was his most memorable experience.
And he and Bones talked about that in later years when they got reacquainted when Bones was the AD.
Did, when you were a student, what did you hear about the 12th man origin?
Did you hear, did Colonel Andy ever talk about it?
Did anybody ever talk about the origin of the 12th man up in the, that game in Dallas?
No, Colonel Andy never did.
The football coaches would, and of course the Yale leaders.
And it was in the cadence.
Okay.
And it was in the Aggieland, which up until my freshman year had been called the Longhorn.
Oh, do you have any idea how that change came about?
Who proposed it?
How, why?
It occurred between 48 and 49 because the 48-year book was called The Longhorn.
Oh, so you got here in the...
I got here in the fall of 48.
Had it already been decided?
Yes, it had.
It was going to be Aggieland because the student senate and I guess the
I don't know, maybe the football players, but certainly the student senate and a lot of other students on campus said, this is crazy, calling our yearbook the Longhorn.
See, and I have assumed that the origin of that name for this institution's yearbook predated the athletic
nomenclature.
I'll bet that book goes back before there were mascot names of Longhorns.
Because I think it goes back to the late 1880s, I think.
But that's just my guess.
I wouldn't be at all surprised.
I don't know when the Longhorns started calling themselves the Longhorns.
I don't either.
Let's see.
All right.
Then we'll go back to some other things that I had written down.
Your senior ring, you got that in the end of your junior year.
How much did it cost?
Where'd you get the money?
Well, I earned the money by...
Building a sewage system out near Easterwood Airport.
I don't know what it was called then, but you would call it environmental services or something like that today.
Sanitation engineering.
Between my fall and spring semesters, since I was exempt from finals, I would
take whatever job I could get.
Well, the engineering extension service or whatever branch of that, they were experimenting with different types of sewage disposal.
And they had a sludge pit out there where the big arm would go around the sludge pit and the effluent would drain off through a pipe and they wanted me to construct a flume
and fill that flume up with gravel and have it go through a series of twists and turns to see so that they could measure the oxygen input at the beginning where it entered this flume.
And I'd have to grade it myself.
I had to do all the work myself.
I had to get it done in two weeks time.
And the thing was about 50 feet
linearly, but with all the twists and turns in it, probably a hundred feet.
And then they would measure the oxygen content at the end of the run to see whether or not that type of a system would work.
Whether it did or not, I don't know.
I just built the thing.
I didn't use it.
senior ring from that, and I have a receipt here.
The ring cost $29.84.
Tax included because that was pre-sales tax.
How did you feel when you put it on?
I was on top of the world, and my father-in-law at the same time gave me the money to buy
My senior boots.
And I bought a used pair of senior boots.
They were in good condition.
And I had the calves adjusted to fit my legs.
They did that at Hollick's Boot Shop.
By what did they cost?
I paid $60 for a two-year-old set of boots.
Including the spurs.
And did you keep those boots or did you sell them?
I've still got them.
You've still got them.
I've got them in a case out in the garage.
With your ring, have you got any good ring stories?
Did you ever lose it?
I lost it for about two weeks.
It was about five or six years ago.
It was a cold day.

in Travis County and uh I'd been wearing tight fitting kid gloves and I came in the house and I was taking off my coat and I took off my gloves and because my hands were so cold my fingers had shrunk and the ring slipped off of my finger but I didn't realize it and uh
Later on that night, I realized that my ring was missing.
And I was really torn up about it because I prized that ring above everything.
Plus, my wife had, after I gave her a bigger diamond, she had given me the diamond out of her engagement ring to put in it.
Oh, my.
And, oh, I fretted and fretted over that.
And about four or five months later,
I had dropped a piece of the vacuum cleaner in the hall closet where we kept our coats, and the piece of the vacuum cleaner rolled back behind the door jamb.
And I was reaching back there for that piece of the vacuum cleaner, and doggone, that ring wasn't there along with it.
Have you been to some special place ever where somebody far, far away recognized
Oh, all over the world.
Examples?
Oh, examples.
Over in Germany, a particular job that I had put me in contact with a lot of Army officers.
And of course, I guess there were probably more Aggies in the Army than there were in the Air Force or the Navy.
Aggies are always on the lookout for somebody else.
with a ring, and we would spot that ring, and that's just the way it worked out.
Other places where some non-Aggie spotted it?
No, non-Aggie didn't know what it was.
They would admire the rings, oh gee, that's a beautiful ring, where's it from?
And I'd explain it to them.
Why are Aggie rings so special?
That's hard to say.
I have noted that Aggie seniors, more Aggie seniors wear Aggie rings than other seniors of other institutions wear their senior rings.
I don't know whether it's because of pride or just what it is.
I'd have to attribute it to a large extent to pride.
and what the ring meant to them personally and what you had to do to get it.
Now when you put on those senior boots and went to final review as a junior, how did you feel?
On top of the world.
On top of the world.
Okay, then as a senior, describe final review your senior year as you recall it.
Who was here and
Let's see, President Eisenhower was here for final review in 1950.
Oh, describe that as far as you remember it.
He was the president of Columbia University.
He was not President Eisenhower at that time.
And he came here to be the reviewing officer.
He was up on the reviewing stand.
The MSC was under construction at that time and he had his entourage of horse holders and of course all of the system officials and school officials were up there.
We common peons didn't get to didn't get to greeting very much, but he made an address
to the entire student body later on after he spoke at the final review.
Then he met with us all in Kyle Field.
And that was quite an event.
Did he say any special things about Aggies?
He paid very great homage to Texas A&M traditions, Aggies that he had run into in the service.
and I don't recall that he singled any out by name.
I'm sure he must have mentioned Earl Rudder, but I don't recall it.
All right, then commencement.
Commencement, we had a commencement speaker.
Don't remember who he was.
Don't remember what he said.
It was held out there in...
Kyle Field.
Gerald, Gerald Natardis was our valedictorian and he gave the valedictorian address.
One of the most inspiring talks I ever heard and it was printed in the
I believe it was printed in the yearbook.
If it's not in the yearbook, I know we all got a copy of it.
And it was very inspiring.
And we walked across the stage.
We had already... No, we had not yet gotten our commissions.
And we got our commissions the following day.
commencement was on the 30th, final review was on the 30th, and we got our commissions on the 31st of May in Guyon Hall.
And... Every hand, every name was called and every hand was shaken.
It was.
And here is a picture of newly commissioned Second Lieutenant Paul Lemming on the steps of Guyon Hall with his mother on his left and his wife on his right.
I had been a second lieutenant for ten minutes.
And each lady had on a hat?
All ladies wore hats and gloves in those days.
And look how thin that young hurdler was in those days.
Well, if you ran as much as I did, you'd be thin.
What did you probably weigh then?
When I graduated, I gained four pounds from my freshman year to my senior year.
I weighed 176.
Which in those days was pretty big.
Yeah, I guess so.
Never thought about it.
As you are getting ready then to leave this campus and go into the real world, how well prepared did you think A&M had made you?
I didn't think that there was any problem that I could not tackle.
work it out, either by myself or with somebody else's cooperation.
And the problem-solving skills, although we didn't call it that then, but the cooperation and teamwork and leadership that we had had passed down to us, it was something else.
Now, how many B's had you made semester grades?
Do you remember?
Six or seven.
And nothing below a B.
No.
What creates Aggie spirit?
Why are Aggies so proud?
Like the saying goes, from the inside, you can't explain it.
From the outside, you can't understand it.
Are there some events that help to create
that contribute to that?
No, it's the sum total of the Aggie experience, at least as far as I'm concerned.
But in that Aggie experience, are there some special, like Yale practice and muster and silver taps and bonfire and commencement?
All of those things.
And I'm sure that all the folks you've interviewed had probably as difficult a time as I did
defining it, let alone explaining it.
But it's the sum total of the four year experience that you had while you were here.
If you were hired today as a consultant to the decision makers at A&M as to what they should do in the future, what to change or not to change,
to add or not to take away, what advice would you give them?
That's a difficult question to answer because of the environment in which we as a university find ourselves these days and the
have.
I would find it very hard to deal with some of the students or the student situations.
I would say continue on with 2020.
I think we've got a good blueprint.
I have a few minor disagreements with some of them, not enough to make any difference.
What about size, enrollment numbers?
I think if we get much larger than we are right now, we'd be too unwieldy.
I agree with you.
How do you select, then, the... That was the next problem that I was going to address.
I don't know how.
without studying the situation further.
And I regret very much that we have to deny certain students who, in my day, would have been well qualified to attend, had they had the money to enroll.
I don't know how you go about making the cutoff point,

It becomes so unfair to those who don't make it who, because of some quirk of either demographics or maybe they're not the token minority in their high school, or because of Hopwood, they're denied admission.
And this thing can be self-consuming and self-defeating.
But I don't have an answer.

If you could make a major gift to A&M, somebody walks up to you and hands you a check for a million dollars or more, and there's only one condition, you must pass it on to A&M, but you can determine what use will be made of that major gift.
What would you want that gift to do?
What would be your favorite act?
A&M thing to support?
I would use it to establish a law school.
Located geographically where?
We've got plenty of room on this campus.
Oh, you'd put it in college session.
Between here and the Brazos River, we have plenty of room.
Now, having said that,
perhaps College Station, which is not exactly the cultural center of the universe, might not be the best location for it.
From a demographics point of view and from a research point of view, research as far as legal research is concerned.
Of course, we could fill that up over time if we ever got a law school.
But at least I would want to start it here.
